<div class="box box-blue">
  <strong>📖 Cambridge Definition</strong>
  Recursion is when a <strong>function or procedure calls itself</strong> as part of its own definition. Every recursive function MUST have a <strong>base case</strong> (stopping condition) and a <strong>general case</strong> (recursive call with a simpler/smaller input).
</div>

<div class="divider"></div>

<!-- ══ SECTION 2 ══ -->
<hr class="section-rule">
<div class="section-header">
  <div class="section-num">02</div>
  <div>
    <div class="section-title">The 2 Essential Rules — Learn These Cold 🧊</div>
    <div class="section-desc">Miss either one → your code breaks. Every time.</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="step-card step-card-green">
  <span class="step-num">RULE 1</span> <strong>Base Case 🛑</strong> — The condition that STOPS the recursion. Without it, the function calls itself forever and the program crashes (stack overflow!). Think of it as the "STOP sign".
</div>
<div class="step-card step-card-blue">
  <span class="step-num">RULE 2</span> <strong>General Case 🔁</strong> — The part that calls the function again, but with a SMALLER or SIMPLER input. Each call gets closer to the base case. Think of it as "going one level deeper".
</div>

<div class="fun-box fun-box-pink">
  <span class="emoji-big">🎮</span><strong>Video game analogy (for real):</strong><br>
  Imagine a dungeon with floors. You start on floor 5.<br>
  Each time you go down, you check: <em>"Am I on floor 0?"</em> (base case 🛑)<br>
  If NOT → go down one more floor 🔁 (general case)<br>
  When you hit floor 0 → you grab the treasure and come back UP through every floor.<br><br>
  <strong>That's exactly how recursion works.</strong> Down = calling itself. Up = returning values.
</div>

<table class="diff-table">
  <tr><th>Part</th><th>What it does</th><th>Example for factorial(n)</th><th>What happens without it?</th></tr>
  <tr>
    <td><span class="pill pill-green">Base Case 🛑</span></td>
    <td>Stops the recursion. Returns a direct answer with NO recursive call.</td>
    <td><code>if n == 0: return 1</code></td>
    <td>Infinite loop → Stack Overflow crash 💥</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td><span class="pill pill-blue">General Case 🔁</span></td>
    <td>Calls itself with a smaller/simpler input. Gets one step closer to stopping.</td>
    <td><code>return n * factorial(n-1)</code></td>
    <td>Function never does anything useful</td>
  </tr>
</table>

<div class="divider"></div>

<!-- ══ SECTION 3 ══ -->
<hr class="section-rule">
<div class="section-header">
  <div class="section-num">03</div>
  <div>
    <div class="section-title">Factorial — The Classic Example 🧮</div>
    <div class="section-desc">5! = 5 × 4 × 3 × 2 × 1 = 120 — let's trace it step by step</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="fun-box fun-box-blue">
  <span class="emoji-big">🧮</span><strong>What's a factorial?</strong><br>
  <code>4! = 4 × 3 × 2 × 1 = 24</code><br>
  <code>3! = 3 × 2 × 1 = 6</code><br>
  <code>2! = 2 × 1 = 2</code><br>
  <code>1! = 1</code><br>
  <code>0! = 1</code> ← this is our <strong>base case</strong>!<br><br>
  Notice: <code>4! = 4 × 3!</code> and <code>3! = 3 × 2!</code> — it's the SAME pattern each time, just with a smaller number. <strong>That's why recursion is perfect here.</strong>
</div>

<pre class="py"><span class="kw">def</span> <span class="fn">factorial</span>(n):
    <span class="cm"># BASE CASE 🛑 — stop here, return directly, no recursive call</span>
    <span class="kw">if</span> n == <span class="nm">0</span>:
        <span class="kw">return</span> <span class="nm">1</span>
    <span class="cm"># GENERAL CASE 🔁 — call ourselves with a SMALLER number (n-1)</span>
    <span class="kw">else</span>:
        <span class="kw">return</span> n * <span class="fn">factorial</span>(n - <span class="nm">1</span>)

<span class="fn">print</span>(<span class="fn">factorial</span>(<span class="nm">4</span>))   <span class="cm"># → 24</span></pre>

<div class="sec-title" style="margin-top:1.2rem;">🔬 Let's trace factorial(4) — step by step</div>
