<!-- ══ SECTION 6 — BENEFITS / DRAWBACKS ══ -->
<hr class="section-rule">
<div class="section-header">
  <div class="section-num">06</div>
  <div>
    <div class="section-title">Pros &amp; Cons — What Cambridge Will Ask 📋</div>
    <div class="section-desc">Know these for any 2-mark or 4-mark comparison question</div>
  </div>
</div>

<table class="diff-table">
  <tr><th>✅ Benefits of Recursion</th><th>❌ Drawbacks of Recursion</th></tr>
  <tr>
    <td><strong>Shorter, cleaner code</strong> — Recursive solutions are often much shorter than loops. Easier to read for problems that are naturally recursive.</td>
    <td><strong>Uses more memory</strong> — Every call adds a new stack frame. Deep recursion = lots of memory used.</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td><strong>Matches the problem naturally</strong> — Problems like factorial, Fibonacci, and tree traversal are defined recursively. The code mirrors the maths directly.</td>
    <td><strong>Slower than iteration</strong> — Function calls have overhead (saving state, jumping around in memory). A loop is usually faster.</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td><strong>Great for self-similar structures</strong> — Trees, file folders, mazes — anything where the same structure repeats inside itself.</td>
    <td><strong>Risk of stack overflow 💥</strong> — If base case is missing or never reached, the stack fills up and the program crashes.</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td></td>
    <td><strong>Harder to trace/debug</strong> — Following what happens in each call and what returns when is confusing for beginners.</td>
  </tr>
</table>

